    "body" : "<h2>JavaFX 25</h2>\n<p>Fixed in <a href=\"https://jdk.java.net/javafx25/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JavaFX 25</a> (requires JDK23+). Released 2025-09-15.</p>\n<p>So, after upgrading, the flag shown below will not be needed.</p>\n<p>See <a href=\"https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8345121\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JDK-8345121</a>.</p>\n<h2>JavaFX 24</h2>\n<p>See the\n<a href=\"https://github.com/openjdk/jfx/blob/jfx24/doc-files/release-notes-24.md\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>Release Notes</em></a> for JavaFX 24, which says:</p>\n<p><strong>Known Issues</strong></p>\n<p><strong>JavaFX Warning Printed for Use of Terminally Deprecated Methods in sun.misc.Unsafe</strong></p>\n<p>Running a JavaFX application on JDK 24 will produce a warning the first time any UI Control or complex shape is rendered:</p>\n<pre><code>WARNING: A terminally deprecated method in sun.misc.Unsafe has been called\n...\nWARNING: sun.misc.Unsafe::allocateMemory will be removed in a future release\n</code></pre>\n<p>To disable this warning, pass <code>--sun-misc-unsafe-memory-access=allow</code> to java on the command line. For example:</p>\n<pre><code>java --sun-misc-unsafe-memory-access=allow\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
